  "prompt": "Is there a map that would take a computer days to draw using 4 colors?",
  "response": "The **Four Color Theorem** states that any map drawn on a plane can be colored using no more than four colors in such a way that no two adjacent regions share the same color. However, the theorem itself doesn't impose any computational complexity related to the size of the map.\n\nThe question of whether there's a map that would take a computer days to color using four colors depends on the **algorithm** used and the **complexity** of the map. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. **Complexity of the Map**:\n   - If the map has an extremely large number of regions (millions or billions) and very complex adjacency relationships, coloring it could be computationally intensive.\n   - However, most maps (even large ones) can be colored efficiently with existing algorithms.\n\n2. **Algorithm Efficiency**:\n   - There are well-known algorithms (e.g., backtracking, greedy, heuristics) that can color maps using four colors in polynomial time.\n   - For example, a greedy algorithm can typically color a map in O(n) time, where \\( n \\) is the number of regions.\n\n3. **Special Cases**:\n   - If the map is designed to be pathological (e.g., intentionally constructed to maximize computational complexity), it might slow down the algorithm.\n   - However, such cases are rare and contrived.\n\n### Conclusion:\nIn practice, most maps can be colored using four colors in a matter of **seconds or minutes**, even for very large maps. It would take an exceptionally large and complex map, combined with an inefficient algorithm, to require days of computation. Such a scenario is not typical but theoretically possible.",
